text.tspan: The whole concept of maritime safety is generally regarded as the prevention of disasters which could result in the loss of life, thevessel, her cargo, as well as damage to the environment. The emergencies may be classified as follows:a) Marine IncidentsIncidents may include fatalities or serious injuries to the company and other personnel; vessel collision, allision or grounding; fire/explosion; and/ or the loss of oil, gas or chemical cargoes from primary containment. Other events proximate to a vessel may alsogive rise to a company emergency, where the circumstances impact company and/ or company interests. In all cases, both the vesseland a potentially broad range of business issues will be dealt with.b) Non Marine IncidentsCompany may be involved in events not specifically connected with a vessel where there is a potential or real risk to people, theenvironment, property and business. These encompass fatalities or injuries to staff working at company’s facilities or offices, and whiletravelling; civil unrest events that may affect company’s people or assets; information security threats; and general loss or damage tofacilities.c) Broader Emergency IssuesThe Head Office is considered the centre of marine expertise for the company and offers advice on request to other offices and legalentities, on marine related matters of concern. In addition, there may be events occurring within or external to the company that couldbe of concern to the company. These may include emergencies involving third party vessels and facilities, events occurring near tocompany assets; or other situations that could put company interests at risk.It is imperative that as soon as any vessel or entity is faced with a situation for potential disaster or is involved in an accident, promptand effective measures are taken to prevent a disaster or mitigate the effects of the accident that has occurred.This section has been prepared to enable the company to respond to contingencies in a well organised, co-ordinated and effectivemanner and to provide a follow-up reference for individuals who are to respond to emergencies and covers all risks to people,environment, property and business, except for matters related specifically to security or to wider business continuity planning.It also contains the necessary information on how the company provides marine and technical support for emergencies primarilyinvolving vessels under management.The Company’s Crisis Management and Emergency Response System priorities are always:· People· Environment· Property· BusinessThe ‘Crisis Management Emergency Response’ process is to:· React· Assess· Respond· Based on this identification, contingency plans are available in Emergency and Contingency Planning Manual and inthis section.7.2INITIAL NOTIFICATION AND 24 HOURS CASUALTY RESPONSE NUMBERIn the event of any contingency the Master shall:1) Immediately notify the office through the 24 Hour Casualty Response Number and provide the required Initial Information.(Note: The above information is available in the Poster GP 28 / GP 28A as applicable for the vessel and a copy should be displayedat the GMDSS Station and known to all concerned persons.)
